Hmmm, INTC doesn't support this now, but that's a great idea!

For now, you'd have to work around it by providing your own property, something like:

MemoryStream Media  
{  
 get { return intc.IsCompleted ? intc.Result : new MemoryStream(); }  
}

And then raise the property changed event for that property when the intc.TaskCompleted is done:

private Task RaiseMediaPropertyChangedWhenIntcCompletesAsync()  
{  
 await intc.TaskCompleted;  
 RaisePropertyChanged("Media");  
}

Hi. Great post! I'm using AsyncLazy<t> for property caching, just like you described. But I also need to reset the property value, and I've not seen anything in the class for that (BTW, it's the same for Lazy<t>, there are ways but it would also be practical...).

Anyway I've added a Reset() method that just does  
 _mutex = new object();  
 _instance = new Lazy<task<t>>(_factory);

but I'm wondering if that method itself shouldn't be locked (using another object than _mutex?)?  
